 @In Düb , According to the World Resources Institute's CAIT carbon tracker, China emitted 11.71 gigatonnes of CO2-equivalent in 2018, which represented 23.9% of global emissions. In comparison, the US, India and European Union (27 countries) emitted 5.79 GTn (11.8%), 3.35 GTn (6.9%) and 3.33 GTn (6.8%) gigatonnes, respectively. Even if we look at per capita emissions, China emitted 8.40 tonnes, compared to 17.74 tonnes in the US, 2.47 tonnes in India and 7.46 tonnes in the EU (27), and the global average is 6.5 tonnes.  
See: https://www.climatewatchdata.org/ghg-emissions?end_year=2018&regions=WORLD&sectors=total-including-lucf&start_year=1990

According to the Global Carbon Project, 13% of China's emissions are caused by its exports. If we reduce China's emissions by 13%, that means that the per capita emissions in China are  7.31 tonnes, which is about the same as the EU's average emissions, and still higher than the global average. China has a serious ecological problem an needs to solve it. Of course, the US has far worse emissions per capita, which is why each country needs to focus on its own emissions, but that doesn't absolve the Chinese of its own responsibility.

